    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-18T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-18T02:00:00-05:00" n="667"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d667">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.942/476: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-18T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 18, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 18—6:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>28. The Foreign Ambassadors were received individually by the Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs<note n="7" xml:id="d667fn7">Hachiro Arita.</note> today merely
                    to pay their respects. Arita said that he desired to carry on with me the
                    conversations begun by his predecessor and would set a date in due course. He
                    said that he had instructed the Japanese Ambassador in Washington to call on you
                    and to endeavor to arrange for a continuation of the present status of “treaty
                    merchants” after the treaty of 1911 expires. A change in their status, he said,
                    would injure both countries.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
